Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry all produce.

Trim and halve @Zucchini{2%unit}; scoop out seeds with a #spoon{} and discard. Rub each
half all over with a drizzle of @Olive Oil{7%teaspoon}; season with half the
@Tuscan Heat Spice{1%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest later), @Salt{} and @Pepper{}.
Arrange cut sides down on a #baking sheet{}.

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

While zucchini roasts, peel and mince or grate @Garlic{1%clove}. Finely dice
@Roma Tomato{2%unit}.

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add
@Israeli Couscous{3/4%cup}, garlic, half the tomatoes, and remaining Tuscan
Heat Spice. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @Veggie Stock Concentrate{1%unit}, 3/4 cup water, and a big pinch of salt.
Bring to a simmer, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook until couscous is
tender, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Turn off heat. Drain any excess liquid from pot if necessary.

Meanwhile, in a #medium bowl{}, combine remaining tomatoes, a large drizzle of
olive oil, and @Balsamic Glaze{5%teaspoon} to taste (save a bit for serving if
desired). Season with salt and pepper.

Season couscous with salt and pepper. Remove zucchini from oven and heat broiler
to high.

Flip zucchini; carefully blot out any excess liquid with #paper towels{}. Stuff
zucchini with as much couscous as will fit (save the rest for serving). Sprinkle
with @Italian Cheese Blend{1/2%cup}.

Broil until cheese is melted and lightly browned, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> TIP: Watch carefully to avoid burning.

Divide remaining couscous between plates and top with stuffed zucchini. Top with
bruschetta and drizzle with any remaining balsamic glaze to taste. Serve.